Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)

Exploratory Data Analysis can be considered an iterative process or cycle in which we examine data to try to discover patterns, find anomalies, test hypotheses, and check assumptions. We can use the tools we’ve learned, namely visualization and transformation of data. We’ll go deeper into this in future weeks, but we have enough skills to try to do some of this now.

The author of our textbook suggests that EDA can follow the following cycle: 1. Generate questions about your data. 2. Search for answers by visualizing, transforming, and modeling your data. 3. Use what you learn to refine your questions and/or generate new questions.

The author of the text also says that the key to asking quality questions is to generate a large quantity of questions! Doing this takes practice. Practice I hope that will start in this class.

Given a new set of data, here are some questions you may ask: - What values are most common? Why? - What values are most rare? Why? - Does what I’m finding match my expectations? - Are there any unusual patters? If so, are there any explanations for these? - What type of variation occurs in my variables. - What type of covariation occurs between my variables.

Visualizing Distributions

Single Variable - Categorical

What can you say about marital status of the individuals included in our bodymeas data set?

ggplot(bodymeas) + geom_bar(aes(x = marital)) # very cluttered x-axis

ggplot(bodymeas) + geom_bar(aes(y = marital))

Can you find the exact counts of each type of marital status given?

bodymeas %>% group_by(marital) %>% summarize(num = n())

Can you generate a chart using this chart/data frame?

o <- bodymeas %>% group_by(marital) %>% summarize(num = n())
ggplot(o) + geom_col(aes(x = num, y = marital))


# or equivalently
ggplot(o) + geom_bar(aes(x = num, y = marital), stat = "identity")

Single Variable - Numerical

Play with different numerical variables, such as weight or height to see what you can tell about the values? Which are most common? Are there any patterns? Does this match our expectations?

ggplot(bodymeas) + geom_histogram(aes(x = weight), binwidth = 1)

Compare what you get using geom_histogram(), geom_freqpoly(), and geom_density(). How can you change bin widths and does doing so change what we say about the data?

ggplot(bodymeas) + geom_freqpoly(aes(x = weight), binwidth = 1)

ggplot(bodymeas) + geom_density(aes(x = weight))

In addition to filtering data to look at subgroups, we can also consider adjusting our \(x\) or \(y\) axes using coord_cartesian(xlim = c(xmin,xmax)) or similarly for our \(y\)-axes values.

What if you use a boxplot and break this up by marital status or race? We can also rearrange the order in which the individual boxplots occur by using the reorder() function.

ggplot(bodymeas) + geom_boxplot(aes(x = weight, fill = marital))

#ggplot(bodymeas) + 
#  geom_boxplot(aes(x = reorder(weight, marital), fill = marital))

Discrete Variables with Many Values

What happens if you try to get an idea of the ages of individuals represented in our bodymeas data?

ggplot(bodymeas) + geom_histogram(aes(x = age), binwidth = 10)

Find a way to create a chart of ages broken down by the decade of age (i.e. ages 50, 51, 52, … 59 would all just be considered 50 (for the 50’s decade))

bodymeas %>% mutate(decade = (age %/% 10) * 10) %>% group_by(decade) %>% summarize(count = n()) %>% ggplot() + 
  geom_col(aes(x = decade, y = count))

Looking for Variation/Relations Between Variables (Covariation)

Between Categorical and Continuous Variables

We’ve played with this a good bit with ggplot(), we can break out a continuous variable by categorical value. Use the coasters data frame to get an idea of the top speed of roller coasters based on the type of construction?

ggplot(coasters) + geom_density(aes(x = speed)) + facet_wrap(~construction)
Warning: Removed 138 rows containing non-finite values (stat_density).

ggplot(coasters) + geom_density(aes(x = speed, color = construction))
Warning: Removed 138 rows containing non-finite values (stat_density).

Between Categorical and Categorical Variables

Use the coasters data set and use geom_tiles() to make a visualization of the average speed of roller coasters broken down by construction and number of inversions.

coasters %>% 
  group_by(construction, numinversions) %>% 
  summarize(avg_speed = mean(speed, na.rm = TRUE)) %>%
ggplot() + 
  geom_tile(aes(x = construction, y = numinversions, fill = avg_speed))
`summarise()` has grouped output by 'construction'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.

What about using this technique for visualizing the number of people in our bodymeas set based on race and maritial status?
